did.abstract: Physical chemists. Writings, speeches, correspondence, research data, subject files, photographs, notes, and miscellaneous textual materials in both physical and digital formats primarily relating to the Karles’ careers at the Naval Research Laboratory and their contributions to the field of crystallography.

acqinfo.head: Acquisition Information
acqinfo.p: The papers of Isabella Karle and Jerome Karle were transferred to the Library of Congress by the Naval Research Laboratory of the United States Navy in 2009. Additional items were transferred in 2010.

processinfo.head: Processing History
processinfo.p: The papers of Isabella Karle and Jerome Karle were arranged and described by Nate Scheible with the assistance of Elizabeth Livesey, Colleen Benoit Kim, Maria Farmer, and Kimberly Owens in 2021.

Digital files were received as part of the Isabella Karle and Jerome Karle Papers on a variety of storage media, each of which was assigned a unique digital ID number. Use the digital ID number to request access copies of the files associated with each media. A description of the standard processes taken on all born digital records can be found in the Processing History Note: Born Digital Collection Material at https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.mss/eadmss.digital.
Some media were damaged and corrupt. Staff disk imaged these media and extracted the files from the disk image.

separatedmaterial.head: Transfers
separatedmaterial.p: Audiovisual materials have been transferred to the Motion Picture, Broadcasting, and Recorded Sound Division where they are identified as part of the Isabella Karle and Jerome Karle Papers. Patrons are encouraged to contact the Motion Picture, Broadcasting, and Recorded Sound Division in advance of a research visit.

userestrict.head: Copyright Status
userestrict.p: The status of copyright in the unpublished writings of Isabella Karle and Jerome Karle is governed by the Copyright Law of the United States (Title 17, U.S.C.).

accessrestrict.head: Access and Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: The Isabella Karle and Jerome Karle Papers are open to research. Many collections are stored off-site and advance notice is needed to retrieve these items for research use. Researchers are advised to contact the Manuscript Reading Room prior to visiting.

phystech.head: Technical Requirements
phystech.p: Digital files were created in a variety of operating systems. The content is primarily crystallographic data in .cif, .cw2, .cdx formats, text files in .doc, .txt, and .pdf formats, image files in .jpg and .tif formats, and presentations in .ppt format.

At the time of processing many of the files were inaccessible through available software. Many of these files contain crystallographic data created in programs from the 1980s to the early 2000s. As a result, these raw versions of the files do not appear as intended in their original hardware and software environments and often include altered formatting and extraneous characters. Files in .cdx format created in the program ChemDraw are not accessible.
One 8” floppy disk and thirteen computer tapes received with this collection are currently unprocessed due to lack of required hardware and not available for research.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Researchers wishing to cite this collection should include the following information: Container or digital ID number, Isabella Karle and Jerome Karle Papers, Manuscript Division, Library of Congress, Washington, D.C.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The papers of Isabella Karle and Jerome Karle span the years 1912-2012, with the bulk of the material dating from 1948 to 2008. The collection documents the Karles’ sixty-five year careers as physical chemists in the field of x-ray crystallography, most of which was spent at the Laboratory for the Structure of Matter at the Naval Research Laboratory (NRL) in Washington, DC. The papers are primarily in English, with Polish and some German, Russian, Spanish, and Chinese. The papers are organized into four series: Isabella Karle Papers, Jerome Karle Papers, Collaborations, and Oversize.

The collection focuses almost entirely on the Karles’ professional careers with little documentation of their personal lives. With the exception of the files in the Collaborations series, Isabella and Jerome maintained separate files which are arranged into distinct series, the Isabella Karle Papers and the Jerome Karle Papers. Both of their papers reflect the development and use of methods for crystal structure analysis with Jerome’s work skewing more toward theoretical investigations and Isabella’s work involving the development and execution of specific processes to analyze crystal structures, most of which were based on Jerome’s theories and calculations. Furthermore, Isabella’s papers focus mostly on her work within the laboratory, while Jerome’s reflect his wider involvement in the field as an administrator and participant in a variety of professional organizations and institutions. Though their working relationship is rarely evidenced in the files, it is explored through oral history interviews and other biographical materials throughout the collection. There is no documentation in the collection of their involvement with the Manhattan Project or other aspects of their career outside the NRL.

The Isabella Karle Papers series documents Karle’s scientific contributions to the field of x-ray crystallography and chiefly includes research and writing files produced at NRL, mostly between 1960 and 2008.

The Jerome Karle Papers document Karle’s contributions to the field of crystallography, his administrative career at NRL, and involvement in numerous scientific organizations, mostly between 1948 and 2008.
The Collaborations series contains materials related to projects, writings, speeches, and presentations on which Isabella and Jerome participated together, the bulk of which span from 1950 to 2009.
The remaining series contains Oversize files.

scopecontent.p: The Isabella Karle Papers series documents Karle’s scientific contributions to the field of x-ray crystallography and chiefly includes research and writing files produced at NRL, mostly between 1960 and 2008. Her papers include articles, correspondence, awards, performance appraisals, biographical sketches, oral history transcripts, professional membership files, and presentations given at scientific and academic conferences. The bulk of Isabella Karle’s series is represented by her Research File, which contains a significant volume of raw crystallographic data, notes, figures and illustrations of molecular structures, and correspondence with scientific collaborators at a variety of national and international institutions. Aside from a small number of biographical sketches and oral history transcripts, there are no files that document Karle’s childhood, personal and family life, education, or her work on the Manhattan Project.

The Personal File subseries contains materials that provide a broad overview of Isabella Karle’s career, mostly between 1970 and 2008. Files include awards and nominations, résumés, oral history transcripts, biographical sketches, and photographs. Of particular interest are Karle’s performance reviews and project reports from NRL that provide succinct overviews of her research, publications, speaking engagements, and other professional activities. Other materials document her involvement in various scientific societies including the National Academy of Sciences, the American Philosophical Society, and the American Crystallographic Association. Additional biographical materials related to Karle can be found in the Collaborations series and include awards, clippings, and oral history interviews.

Material types include résumés, awards, certificates, oral history transcripts, biographical sketches, business cards, photographs, correspondence, memoranda, reports, applications, clippings, notes, calendars, and schedules. Some visual materials are in digital formats.

arrangement.p: Arranged alphabetically by subject or material type. The file structure of the digital content maintained as received.

scopecontent.p: The Correspondence subseries comprises professional correspondence received by Isabella Karle, mostly spanning from 1965 to 2000. The bulk of the subseries contains incoming letters from colleagues, publishers, and other scientists in her field. Topics documented include her research interests, status of projects and publications, involvement in professional organizations, arrangements for speaking engagements, biographical sketches, and referee comments by and for Karle. The subseries is not comprehensive, and most correspondence related to specific research, writings, speeches, and subjects can be found within files maintained according to topic throughout the series. Most letters addressed to both Isabella and Jerome can be found in the Collaborations series.
Material types include letters, email printouts, memoranda, invitations, and attachments including writings, programs, and itineraries.

arrangement.p: Arranged alphabetically by subject, the bulk of which is a chronological file.

scopecontent.p: The Speeches and Writings subseries comprises files related to articles, reports, speeches, lectures, and book chapters written by Isabella Karle, mostly from 1960 to 2003. The files contain drafts, working files, figures, illustrations, research data, notes, abstracts, and correspondence. Frequent collaborators represented in the subseries include Darshan Ranganathan, Subramania Ranganathan, Padmanabhan Balaram, and Bernhard Witkop. The bulk of the speeches and writings correspond to the molecular structure analyses contained in Karle’s Research File. Published structures of these complex organic and inorganic substances include steroids, alkaloids, toxins, ionophores, and, especially, peptides, and relate to such varied topics as the transport of ions, protection against radiation damage, energetic and propellant materials, antimalarials, antibiotics, non-addicting analgesics, shock, neurotoxins, explosives, and nitrogen compounds. Also present in the subseries are Isabella’s lecture files from a variety of x-ray crystallography study institutes, many of which include lectures she presented with Jerome Karle. For additional materials from these study institutes, as well as writings and speeches written in collaboration with Jerome, see the Collaborations series. Additional writings, speeches, and related materials are interspersed throughout the Research File and Subject File.

Material types include articles, notes, research, data, figures, illustrations, correspondence, conference programs, abstracts, speeches, travel files, photographs, and bibliographies. Some textual and visual materials are in digital formats.

scopecontent.p: The Subject File subseries comprises files from a variety of Karle’s professional efforts, and include name files, travel files, grant files, and slides. Name files contain correspondence, draft publications, notes, clippings, photographs, and crystallographic data related to specific projects undertaken by Karle and the identified individual. Travel files largely consist of Defense Department memoranda that detail Karle’s attendance at conferences, meetings, award ceremonies, and lecture engagements. Grant files include applications, progress reports, and correspondence related to the National Institutes of Health-funded “X-Ray Diffraction Studies of Oligopeptides” project from 1981 to 2008. The subseries also contains referee comments and recommendations by Karle. Of particular interest are the recommendations Karle wrote for her daughters Louise Karle Hanson and Jean Karle Dean, both of whom pursued careers in the field of chemistry. The associated correspondence in these files contains some of the only references in the collection to Jerome and Isabella Karle’s family life. Slides, arranged by subject, likely relate to speeches, lectures, and presentations though are not identified as such.

Material types include correspondence, publications, notes, clippings, slides, photographs, research data, memoranda, applications, reports, letters of recommendation, and travel files. Some textual materials are in digital formats

scopecontent.p: The Research File subseries represents the bulk of the materials found in the Isabella Karle Papers and chiefly comprises Karle’s extensive x-ray crystallography research data, mostly from 1960 to 2006. Given the technical nature of her research the subseries is largely arranged as received with the original file names retained in order to preserve context. An alternate alphabetical arrangement of the subseries can be found at https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.mss/eadmss.ms021006.apx. Molecular structures represented include Leu-enkephalin, valinomycin, lysozyme, antamanide, batrachotoxinin A, and synthetic analogs of antamanide, cycloamanide, hexapeptides, and depsipeptides. The Research File also includes publications, draft writings, correspondence, lecture notes, slides, and other materials related to the collected raw data. Project and funding reports related to Isabella’s research can be found in Jerome Karle’s NRL files within the Organizations and Institutions subseries.

Material types include crystallographic data printouts, photographs, negatives, slides, diffractograms, notes, correspondence, reports, memoranda, lectures, figures, illustrations, writings, and clippings. Some articles, crystallographic data, figures, and illustrations are in digital formats.

scopecontent.p: The Jerome Karle Papers document Karle’s contributions to the field of crystallography, his administrative career at NRL, and involvement in numerous scientific organizations, mostly between 1948 and 2008. The series features writings, speeches, correspondence, and subject files focusing on his research in structural chemistry, highlighting his work in crystal structure determination and the development of various diffraction techniques. It also comprises files pertaining to his roles in developing national and international science policy within the National Academy of Sciences, International Union of Crystallography, and American Academy of Crystallography.

The Personal File subseries contains materials that are primarily biographical and provide an overview of Jerome Karle’s life and career. Files include biographical sketches, awards, résumés, photographs, and clippings. The subseries documents Karle’s winning of the Nobel Prize in chemistry in 1985 (shared with Herbert A. Hauptman), including his subsequent involvement at various events as a Nobel laureate. Lectures presented at meetings of Nobel laureates in Lindau, Germany, are filed within the Speeches and Writings subseries. Additional biographical materials related to Karle can be found in the Collaborations series and include awards, clippings, and oral history interviews.
Material types include résumés, awards, certificates, clippings, business cards, calendars, photographs, bibliographies, and correspondence.

scopecontent.p: The Correspondence subseries comprises professional correspondence received by Karle, the bulk of which spans from 1965 to 2000. Although some outgoing letters are included, the subseries largely consists of letters sent to Karle by colleagues, scientists, and admirers of his work, especially after he won the Nobel Prize. Topics include solicitation for comments on articles, vacancy announcements, arrangements for speaking engagements and conference appearances, reprint requests, and letters from individuals seeking his autograph or advice. Additional correspondence related to the Nobel Prize can be found in the Personal File. The bulk of the correspondence in this subseries is of a general nature. Letters and memoranda related to Karle’s career at NRL and within professional organizations are filed in relevant folders in the Organizations and Institutions subseries, and correspondence tied to specific projects or topics can be found within associated materials in the Subject File. Most letters addressed to both Isabella and Jerome can be found in the Collaborations series.
Material types include letters, email printouts, memoranda, invitations, and greeting cards.

arrangement.p: Arranged alphabetically by subject, the bulk of which is a chronological file.

scopecontent.p: The Speeches and Writings subseries comprises files related to articles, lectures, abstracts, reports, and a monograph written by Karle focusing on a range of topics relevant to his crystallography research. The bulk of the materials span from 1950 to 2000. In addition to published and unpublished writings, the files contain drafts, working files, correspondence, research, and other background material. Topics explored focus mostly on x-ray diffraction, gas electron diffraction, electron diffraction, anomalous dispersion, and quantum mechanics. Some writings focus on the analysis of crystal and molecular structure of specific compounds. Frequent collaborators represented in the subseries include Herbert A. Hauptman, Lou Massa, Lulu Huang, Richard Gilardi, John Konnert, Wayne Hendrickson, and Judith Flippen-Anderson. Speech files mostly include lectures presented at conferences, symposia, and workshops. Lectures related to classes taught by Karle at the University of Maryland can be found in the Organizations and Institutions subseries. Writings and speeches prepared in collaboration with Isabella Karle are within the Collaborations series.

Material types include articles, abstracts, figures, illustrations, slides, correspondence, reports, presentations, testimonies, and speeches. Some textual and visual materials are in digital formats.

arrangement.p: Arranged alphabetically by material type and thereunder chronologically. The file structure of the digital content maintained as received.

scopecontent.p: The Organizations and Institutions subseries documents Karle’s professional memberships, appointments, involvement in numerous crystallography organizations, and his career as an administrator at NRL, mostly from his appointment as chief scientist within the Laboratory for the Structure of Matter in 1968 through his retirement in 2009. The NRL materials include program reviews, progress reports, proposals, and performance evaluations. The subseries focuses mostly on Karle’s role as administrator at NRL, with research conducted under the auspices of the laboratory filed elsewhere throughout the series where appropriate. Karle held various leadership positions in many national and international crystallography organizations, most notably the International Union of Crystallographers, the American Crystallographic Association, and the United States of America Committee for Crystallography. The bulk of the files in this subseries details his roles within these organizations in the 1970s and 1980s. Karle was also active in general science organizations, most notably the National Academy of Sciences, the files of which focus mostly on his involvement on the Committee on Human Rights, 1991-1997, and as chair of the chemistry section, 1988-1991. Other notable organizations where he was involved on a wider level in affecting national science policy include the International Council of Scientific Unions, the National Research Council, and the National Science Foundation. The subseries also details his involvement on boards and committees at his various alma maters including City College of New York, the University of Michigan, and Abraham Lincoln High School in New York City. There are no files from his time as a student at these institutions. Files related to his involvement with the NATO Advanced Study Institute can be found in the Collaborations series.

Material types include meeting minutes, agendas, notes, correspondence, proposals, conference programs, performance evaluations, itineraries, personnel actions, reports, newsletters, financial documents, ballots, press releases, and presentations. Some textual materials are in digital formats.

scopecontent.p: The Subject File primarily documents Karle’s research activities and interests throughout his career, with an emphasis on his collaborative working relationships at the NRL. The largest group of files in the series are related to Steve Brenner, research chemist at NRL from 1962 to 2007, who collaborated with Karle on computer operations and calculations. The files contain crystallographic data printouts along with notes by Karle. Received in containers labeled “Steve Brenner apps,” the files were arranged chronologically in the order they were received. The folder dates were maintained in order to provide context, especially given their specificity. Researchers should be aware that the actual dates of materials within each folder may vary. A significant research file mostly from the 1950s and early 1960s was also maintained as received. These materials comprise notes, writings, equations, data, and likely relate to Karle’s collaboration with Herbert A. Hauptman on the topic of phase determination. Other significant collaborations in the subseries include Karle’s work with Lulu Huang and Lou Massa on the subject of quantum crystallography in the late 1990s and early 2000s. Specific topics throughout the subseries include anomalous dispersion, electron diffraction, various computational chemistry programs, and projects associated with the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency. The subseries also includes Karle’s recommendation letters and referee comments.

Material types include reports, slides, clippings, notes, correspondence, writings, schedules, laboratory notebooks, articles, pamphlets, and photographs. Some textual materials are in digital formats.

arrangement.p: Arranged alphabetically by subject. The file structure of the digital content maintained as received.

scopecontent.p: The Collaborations series contains materials related to projects, writings, speeches, and presentations on which Isabella and Jerome participated together, the bulk of which span from 1950 to 2009. The series contains many files related to their involvement as instructors with the International School of Crystallography and NATO Advanced Study Institute from the 1960s through the 1980s. Biographical materials that provide insight into their working relationship include oral history interview transcripts, clippings, and interviews. Other notable topics and material types include C₂Cl₆ research, travel engagements, retirement information, correspondence, and awards.
Material types include awards, transcripts, clippings, photographs, correspondence, articles, presentations, speeches, lectures, notes, and schedules.
